Project Members: Kyle Chang and Ryan Anderson

2. How are you using your sensors to intelligently react to the user's environment and "assist" the user?

We are monitoring the accelerator sensor of the phone, specifically in the X direction,
along with their location and local weather data. We also ask the user to input whether
they own an umbrella or snow boots. We check in the X value spikes to a certain number
the user is getting up and moving, possibly outside. When this happens, we check the
user’s local weather using their location and the OpenWeather API. So if the user goes
outside and it’s snowy, the app reminds them to “get their snow boots” or, if they don’t
own snow boots, to “buy some snow boots.” The same things for the umbrella if it is raining.
Just a reminder app so you go outside prepared.

3. Any instructions that we should know on how to run/use your application?

Create an OpenWeather account so you can use their API to retrieve current weather data for
a given location, and follow the documentation for each application to set up API access.
Add your API key to the root project directory in local.properties using the format
OPENWEATHER_API_KEY=.... After adding the key, run a Clean and Build so the settings load
correctly. Complete this step early, because API keys can take up to six hours to become active.
Set the user location to a city location, not a specific place in the city. Boot up the app,
you will be asked to give permission for the app to track your location. Please allow it to do
so. Then go to the settings and toggle whether you have an umbrella and snow shoes. Now you're done!



4. Any references/resources used. I highly doubt this section will be blank,
   since there is so much we didn't cover in this class!

For the location and OpenWeather API, we repurposed a lot of the code we learned from Project 3,
the “Weather App.” For the accelerometer sensors, so getting the accelerometer X value as a
Foreground service, we used the following sources to construct it:
https://developer.android.com/develop/sensors-and-location/sensors/sensors_overview
https://developer.android.com/develop/background-work/services/fgs

Foreground services require a persistent notification so the user knows the service is running.
We originally planned to use Android’s notification system for user-facing updates, but due to
time and technical constraints, we moved those updates into the View/ViewModel instead. Even if
we are not using custom notification updates, the foreground-service notification code still
must remain in the app because Android requires a notification for the foreground service to
run. We used the following resources to code that:
https://developer.android.com/develop/ui/views/notifications/build-notification
https://developer.android.com/develop/background-work/services/fgs/launch

In order to store useful information about our user that is integral for the functioning of t
he app, we use DataStore. We store the user’s location, whether they own snow boots, and
whether they own an umbrella. To code this, we used the following resources:
https://developer.android.com/topic/libraries/architecture/datastore
https://android-developers.googleblog.com/2020/09/prefer-storing-data-with-jetpack.html
